
DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol)
🎯 Objective

Learn what DHCP is, why it is required, how it works, understand the DHCP process (DORA), and practice Linux commands related to network configuration.

📖 What is DHCP?

DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol) is a network protocol that automatically assigns IP addresses and other network settings (such as subnet mask, default gateway, and DNS server) to devices connected to a network.

Without DHCP, every device would need to be configured manually, which would be time-consuming and error-prone.

Why Do We Need DHCP?

Imagine an office with 500 computers.

Without DHCP:

Every computer must be assigned an IP address manually.
Duplicate IP addresses may cause network conflicts.
Network administration becomes difficult.

With DHCP:

Devices automatically receive valid network settings.
Reduces configuration errors.
Saves time for administrators.
Information Provided by DHCP

A DHCP server typically assigns:

IP Address
Subnet Mask
Default Gateway
DNS Server
Lease Time

Example:

IP Address      : 192.168.1.100
Subnet Mask     : 255.255.255.0
Gateway         : 192.168.1.1
DNS Server      : 8.8.8.8
Lease Time      : 24 Hours
DHCP Working (DORA Process)

DHCP follows a four-step process known as DORA.

Client                  DHCP Server

 |------ DHCP Discover ------>|
 |<------- DHCP Offer ---------|
 |------ DHCP Request -------->|
 |<--------- DHCP ACK ---------|
1. Discover

The client broadcasts a request to find available DHCP servers.

2. Offer

The DHCP server responds with an available IP address and configuration details.

3. Request

The client requests to use the offered IP address.

4. Acknowledgment (ACK)

DHCP Diagram
+-----------+                      +--------------+
|   Client  |                      | DHCP Server  |
+-----------+                      +--------------+
      |                                    |
      |---- DHCP Discover ---------------->|
      |<--- DHCP Offer --------------------|
      |---- DHCP Request ----------------->|
      |<--- DHCP ACK ----------------------|
      |                                    |


DHCP Lease

A lease is the period for which a client can use an assigned IP address.

After the lease expires, the client requests a renewal from the DHCP server.

Advantages of DHCP
Automatic IP assignment
Reduces manual work
Prevents IP conflicts
Simplifies network management
Centralized configuration
Supports large networks

Disadvantages of DHCP
Depends on the availability of the DHCP server.
If the server fails, new devices cannot automatically obtain IP addresses.
Requires proper configuration to avoid network issues.

Linux Commands

View IP Address
ip addr

Show Routing Table
ip route

View DNS Configuration
cat /etc/resolv.conf

Check DHCP Client Status (Ubuntu with systemd)
systemctl status NetworkManager

Renew DHCP Lease (depends on distribution)
sudo dhclient -r
sudo dhclient

Note: dhclient may not be installed on all Linux distributions. Some distributions use NetworkManager or systemd-networkd instead.

The server confirms the assignment and starts the lease.

